PATCH: Better error diagnostics for NanoClaw Slack channel
Apply in: src/channels/slack.ts

=== IMPROVEMENT 1: Scope validation at startup ===
In connect(), replace:
    const auth = await this.app.client.auth.test();
    this.botUserId = auth.user_id as string;
    logger.info({ botUserId: this.botUserId }, 'Connected to Slack');

With:
    const auth = await this.app.client.auth.test();
    this.botUserId = auth.user_id as string;

    // Validate token has all scopes needed for NanoClaw features
    const grantedScopes = ((auth as Record<string, unknown>).scope as string ?? '').split(',');
    const requiredScopes = ['chat:write', 'channels:history', 'files:read'];
    const missingScopes = requiredScopes.filter(s => !grantedScopes.includes(s));
    if (missingScopes.length > 0) {
      logger.warn(
        { missingScopes, grantedScopes },
        `Slack bot token is MISSING required scopes: [${missingScopes.join(', ')}]. ` +
        `Go to api.slack.com/apps → OAuth & Permissions → add scopes → Reinstall to Workspace → update SLACK_BOT_TOKEN in .env`,
      );
    } else {
      logger.info({ botUserId: this.botUserId, scopeCount: grantedScopes.length }, 'Connected to Slack — all required scopes present');
    }

WHY: Would have told us IMMEDIATELY "token missing files:read" instead of
     30 minutes of redirect debugging.

=== IMPROVEMENT 2: Use files.info as fallback when stub lacks url_private_download ===
In downloadSlackFiles(), replace:
    if (!file.url_private_download || !file.name) continue;

With:
    if (!file.name) continue;

    // Slack message events sometimes deliver file stubs without url_private_download.
    // Fall back to files.info API to get the full file object.
    let downloadUrl = file.url_private_download;
    if (!downloadUrl && file.id) {
      try {
        const info = await this.app.client.files.info({ file: file.id });
        downloadUrl = (info.file as Record<string, unknown>)?.url_private_download as string | undefined;
        logger.info({ file: file.name, source: 'files.info' }, 'Got download URL via files.info fallback');
      } catch (err) {
        logger.warn({ file: file.name, err }, 'files.info fallback failed — skipping file');
        continue;
      }
    }
    if (!downloadUrl) {
      logger.warn({ file: file.name, fileId: file.id }, 'No download URL available for Slack file — skipping');
      continue;
    }

WHY: Silently skipping files with no URL caused total invisibility of the problem.

=== IMPROVEMENT 3: Classify download failures clearly ===
In downloadSlackFiles(), replace the contentType HTML check:
    if (contentType.includes('text/html')) {
      logger.warn(
        { file: file.name, contentType, tokenSet: !!this.botToken },
        'Slack file download returned HTML — likely auth failure or bad token',
      );
      continue;
    }

With:
    if (contentType.includes('text/html')) {
      const isAuthRedirect = downloadUrl.includes('slack.com/?redir=') ||
        downloadUrl.includes('slack.com/sign');
      logger.error(
        {
          file: file.name,
          contentType,
          tokenSet: !!this.botToken,
          tokenPreview: this.botToken ? `${this.botToken.slice(0, 8)}...` : 'EMPTY',
          downloadUrl,
          diagnosis: isAuthRedirect
            ? 'TOKEN_MISSING_SCOPE: Reinstall Slack app at api.slack.com/apps after adding files:read'
            : 'AUTH_FAILURE: Check SLACK_BOT_TOKEN is valid and not expired',
        },
        'Slack file download blocked — received HTML instead of file content',
      );
      continue;
    }

WHY: "likely auth failure" is vague. The actionable fix should be IN the log line.

=== AFTER APPLYING ===
Rebuild: npm run build
Restart NanoClaw
Then check logs on next file share — scope issues will appear at startup,
not buried in download attempts.
